---
// src/pages/science/gangliosides.astro
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { useTranslations } from "../../i18n";
import GangliosideMap from "../../components/science/GangliosideMap";

const t = useTranslations('en');
---

<BaseLayout 
  title={t.sections.gangliosides.title}
  description="Interactive visualization of ganglioside biosynthesis and degradation pathways, with focus on GT1b and its role in neuronal transport."
>
  <!-- Page Header -->
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-b from-slate-900 to-slate-800 text-white py-16">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <nav class="text-sm text-slate-400 mb-4">
        <a href="/" class="hover:text-white transition-colors">Home</a>
        <span class="mx-2">/</span>
        <a href="/science/" class="hover:text-white transition-colors">Science</a>
        <span class="mx-2">/</span>
        <span class="text-white">Gangliosides</span>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold mb-4">{t.sections.gangliosides.title}</h1>
      <p class="text-xl text-slate-300 max-w-3xl">
        Understanding the biosynthesis and degradation of gangliosides is crucial for 
        comprehending how vaccine components might be transported through the nervous system.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Introduction -->
  <section class="py-12">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="prose-science">
        <h2>What are Gangliosides?</h2>
        <p>
          Gangliosides are complex sphingolipids containing one or more sialic acid residues. 
          They are abundant in the nervous system, comprising 10-12% of total lipid content in 
          neuronal membranes. Their unique carbohydrate chains serve as receptors for various 
          biological molecules, including bacterial toxins and viruses.
        </p>
        
        <div class="key-concept">
          <div class="key-concept-title">Key Concept: GT1b Ganglioside</div>
          <p class="mb-0">
            GT1b is a trisialoganglioside that serves as the primary receptor for tetanus toxin. 
            Research suggests that H1N1 influenza virus may also bind to GT1b, enabling 
            retrograde axonal transport similar to tetanus toxin.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <h2>The Svennerholm Classification</h2>
        <p>
          Gangliosides are classified using the Svennerholm nomenclature system, where:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>G</strong> = Ganglioside</li>
          <li><strong>M, D, T, Q</strong> = Number of sialic acid residues (Mono, Di, Tri, Quadra)</li>
          <li><strong>1, 2, 3</strong> = Order of migration on chromatography</li>
          <li><strong>a, b, c</strong> = Position of sialic acids on the sugar chain</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>A-Series vs B-Series: Critical Differences</h2>
        <p>
          The distinction between a-series (monosialo) and b-series (disialo) gangliosides is 
          <strong>central to understanding the hypothesis</strong>. These series differ fundamentally 
          in their behavior, localization, and clinical significance.
        </p>

        <table class="w-full text-sm my-6">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b bg-slate-50">
              <th class="text-left py-2 px-2">Property</th>
              <th class="text-left py-2 px-2">A-Series (Monosialo)</th>
              <th class="text-left py-2 px-2">B-Series (Disialo)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr class="border-b">
              <td class="py-2 px-2 font-medium">Examples</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">GM3 ‚Üí GM2 ‚Üí GM1 ‚Üí GD1a</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">GD3 ‚Üí GD2 ‚Üí GD1b ‚Üí GT1b ‚Üí GQ1b</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b">
              <td class="py-2 px-2 font-medium">Key enzyme</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">ST3GAL5 (GM3 synthase)</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">ST8SIA1 (GD3 synthase)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b">
              <td class="py-2 px-2 font-medium">Membrane behavior</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">Stable in lipid rafts</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">Dynamic, prone to export</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b">
              <td class="py-2 px-2 font-medium">Primary location</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">Nodes of Ranvier, myelin</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">Synaptic terminals, oculomotor nerves</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b">
              <td class="py-2 px-2 font-medium">Shedding rate</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2 text-green-600">Low</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2 text-amber-600 font-bold">High</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b">
              <td class="py-2 px-2 font-medium">Storage diseases</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">GM1/GM2 gangliosidosis</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2 text-amber-600 font-bold">None known!</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b bg-red-50">
              <td class="py-2 px-2 font-medium">Immune exposure</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">Lower</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2 text-red-600 font-bold">Higher (Miller Fisher, GBS)</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <div class="key-concept">
          <div class="key-concept-title">The Shedding Mechanism</div>
          <p>
            B-series gangliosides (GD3, GT1b, GQ1b) have a <strong>higher negative charge</strong> 
            due to their two sialic acid residues. This promotes export via extracellular vesicles 
            (EVs/exosomes) through ceramide-dependent budding. This "bypass" of lysosomal 
            degradation has two critical consequences:
          </p>
          <ol class="mt-2 mb-0">
            <li><strong>No lysosomal accumulation</strong> ‚Üí No storage disease phenotype</li>
            <li><strong>Increased extracellular exposure</strong> ‚Üí Higher vulnerability to autoimmune attack</li>
          </ol>
        </div>

        <!-- Key Illustration: A-series vs B-series -->
        <figure class="my-8">
          <img 
            src="/images/intracellular-storage-extracellular-shedding.png" 
            alt="A-series (GM1) leads to intracellular storage in lysosomes, while B-series (GT1b) is exported via exosomes for extracellular communication"
            class="w-full rounded-lg border border-slate-200 shadow-lg"
          />
          <figcaption class="text-sm text-slate-600 mt-3 text-center">
            <strong>The Great Divide:</strong> A-series gangliosides (GM1) are directed to lysosomes 
            for degradation ‚Äî a "dead end" that causes storage diseases when blocked. B-series 
            gangliosides (GT1b) are exported via exosomes for intercellular communication ‚Äî 
            bypassing lysosomal accumulation but increasing immune exposure.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h3>Clinical Evidence: Miller Fisher Syndrome</h3>
        <p>
          Miller Fisher syndrome (MFS) perfectly illustrates the b-series vulnerability. This 
          variant of Guillain-Barr√© syndrome is characterized by:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Clinical triad:</strong> Ophthalmoplegia, ataxia, areflexia</li>
          <li><strong>Anti-GQ1b antibodies:</strong> Present in 85-90% of cases</li>
          <li><strong>Post-infectious trigger:</strong> Often <em>Campylobacter jejuni</em></li>
          <li><strong>Molecular mimicry:</strong> Bacterial lipo-oligosaccharides resemble GQ1b epitopes</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="warning-box">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-amber-800 mb-2">Why Oculomotor Nerves?</h4>
          <p class="text-amber-700 text-sm mb-0">
            The oculomotor nerves and dorsal root ganglia are <strong>enriched in b-series gangliosides</strong> 
            (GT1b, GQ1b). Their high shedding rate increases local immune exposure, explaining the 
            selective vulnerability in MFS. The same mechanism may apply to orexin neurons in 
            post-Pandemrix narcolepsy.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="info-box mt-6">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-blue-800 mb-2">A-Series (GM3) and the Auditory System</h4>
          <p class="text-blue-700 text-sm mb-2">
            GM3 is essential for cochlear function ‚Äî GM3 synthase deficiency causes profound deafness. 
            We explored whether H3N2 influenza (which binds GM3) could explain "Havana Syndrome" via 
            similar ganglioside-mediated mechanisms.
          </p>
          <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm mb-0">
            <strong class="text-red-600">Result:</strong> After critical evaluation, this hypothesis was found 
            <strong>unlikely</strong>. See: <a href="/speculation/havana-syndrome/" class="text-red-600 underline">The Havana Hypothesis (Falsified)</a>
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Interactive Diagram -->
  <section class="py-12 bg-slate-100">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <GangliosideMap 
        client:load
        labels={{
          title: t.sections.gangliosides.title,
          subtitle: t.sections.gangliosides.subtitle,
          biosynthesis: t.sections.gangliosides.biosynthesis,
          degradation: t.sections.gangliosides.degradation,
          clinicalRelevance: t.sections.gangliosides.clinical_relevance,
        }}
      />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Detailed Explanation -->
  <section class="py-12">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="prose-science">
        <h2>Biosynthesis Pathway</h2>
        <p>
          Ganglioside biosynthesis occurs primarily in the Golgi apparatus through sequential 
          addition of sugar residues to ceramide. The pathway branches at LacCer (lactosylceramide), 
          giving rise to different ganglioside series:
        </p>
        
        <h3>Key Enzymes</h3>
        <table class="w-full text-sm">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b">
              <th class="text-left py-2">Gene</th>
              <th class="text-left py-2">Enzyme</th>
              <th class="text-left py-2">Function</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr class="border-b">
              <td class="py-2"><span class="gene-name">ST3GAL5</span></td>
              <td class="py-2">GM3 Synthase</td>
              <td class="py-2">Initiates ganglioside biosynthesis from LacCer</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b">
              <td class="py-2"><span class="gene-name">ST8SIA1</span></td>
              <td class="py-2">GD3 Synthase</td>
              <td class="py-2">Creates b-series gangliosides</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b">
              <td class="py-2"><span class="gene-name">B4GALNT1</span></td>
              <td class="py-2">GM2/GD2 Synthase</td>
              <td class="py-2">Adds GalNAc to extend the sugar chain</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b">
              <td class="py-2"><span class="gene-name">ST3GAL2</span></td>
              <td class="py-2">GD1a/GT1b Synthase</td>
              <td class="py-2">Terminal sialylation creating GT1b</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h2>Degradation Pathway</h2>
        <p>
          Ganglioside degradation occurs in lysosomes through sequential removal of sugar residues. 
          Defects in degradation enzymes lead to lysosomal storage diseases:
        </p>
        
        <div class="info-box">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-blue-800 mb-2">Neuraminidase (Sialidase)</h4>
          <p class="text-blue-700 text-sm mb-0">
            <span class="gene-name">NEU1-4</span> genes encode neuraminidases that remove sialic acid 
            from gangliosides. Variants in these genes, particularly those near the HLA locus, may 
            affect GT1b levels and susceptibility to autoimmune reactions.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h2>The GT1b Paradox ‚Äî No Storage Disease</h2>
        <p>
          A remarkable observation: while most gangliosides have well-characterized storage diseases 
          (GM1 gangliosidosis, Tay-Sachs for GM2), <strong>there is no known primary disease caused 
          by accumulation of GD1b or GT1b</strong>.
        </p>
        
        <div class="key-concept">
          <div class="key-concept-title">Why Does GT1b Not Cause Storage Disease?</div>
          <p>
            GT1b behaves differently from intracellular gangliosides. The mechanism is now understood:
          </p>
          <ol class="mt-2 mb-0">
            <li>
              <strong>EV-mediated shedding:</strong> B-series gangliosides are exported via 
              extracellular vesicles (exosomes, microvesicles) through ESCRT-dependent and 
              ceramide-dependent pathways [5].
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Lysosomal bypass:</strong> This shedding provides a "bypass" of normal 
              lysosomal degradation, preventing intracellular accumulation.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Higher sialic acid charge:</strong> The two sialic acids on b-series 
              gangliosides promote vesicular curvature and membrane budding.
            </li>
          </ol>
        </div>

        <p>
          This explains the paradox: when GT1b levels increase, the excess is <em>exported</em> 
          rather than accumulating in lysosomes. Tetanus toxin (which binds GT1b) is therefore 
          released <strong>outside</strong> nerve terminals, while cholera toxin (which binds GM1) 
          remains <strong>inside</strong>.
        </p>

        <!-- Key Illustration: Cholera vs Tetanus Transport -->
        <figure class="my-8">
          <img 
            src="/images/choleratoxin-tetanus-toxin-transport.jpg" 
            alt="Cholera toxin (GM1) stays intracellular targeting Golgi, while Tetanus toxin (GT1b) is released via signaling endosomes for trans-synaptic jump"
            class="w-full rounded-lg border border-slate-200 shadow-lg"
          />
          <figcaption class="text-sm text-slate-600 mt-3 text-center">
            <strong>Two Toxins, Two Fates:</strong> Cholera toxin (binding GM1) remains intracellular 
            and targets the Golgi network. Tetanus toxin (binding GT1b) is released via signaling 
            endosomes and makes a <em>trans-synaptic jump</em> to neighboring neurons. This is the 
            key difference that enables GT1b-bound substances to spread through neural circuits.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h2>The B-Series as a Communication Highway ‚Äî A Hypothesis</h2>
        <p>
          If B-series gangliosides are "designed" for shedding and extracellular communication, 
          what do they normally carry? <strong>We propose</strong> that the answer has profound 
          implications for understanding how vaccine antigens might reach unexpected destinations.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-400 p-3 my-4 text-sm">
          <strong class="text-amber-800">‚ö†Ô∏è Note:</strong> 
          <span class="text-amber-700">The following "Neurotrophin Highway" concept is a <em>hypothesis</em> 
          proposed here, not established scientific consensus. It builds on known facts about 
          GT1b-neurotrophin interactions but extends them speculatively.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-emerald-50 border border-emerald-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-emerald-800 mb-4">üöÇ The Neurotrophin Cargo ‚Äî What Might Travel on the B-Series Express?</h3>
          <p class="text-emerald-700 text-sm mb-4">
            <strong>Known facts:</strong> Key neurotrophic factors depend on GT1b/GD1b for their signaling:
          </p>
          
          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 mb-4">
            <div class="bg-white rounded p-3 border border-emerald-200">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-emerald-700 mb-1">GDNF</h4>
              <p class="text-slate-600 text-xs">
                <strong>Glial cell line-derived neurotrophic factor.</strong> Critical for dopaminergic 
                neuron survival (Parkinson's research). Requires GD1b/GT1b-rich lipid rafts for 
                GFRŒ±1/RET receptor signaling.
              </p>
              <p class="text-emerald-600 text-[10px] mt-1">
                <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12671643/" target="_blank" class="hover:underline">Sariola & Saarma 2003</a>
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-white rounded p-3 border border-emerald-200">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-emerald-700 mb-1">BDNF</h4>
              <p class="text-slate-600 text-xs">
                <strong>Brain-derived neurotrophic factor.</strong> Essential for plasticity and memory. 
                GT1b is required for TrkB receptor dimerization. Can be shed in <strong>exosomes 
                together with gangliosides</strong>!
              </p>
              <p class="text-emerald-600 text-[10px] mt-1">
                <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21325515/" target="_blank" class="hover:underline">Lim et al. 2011</a>
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-white rounded p-3 border border-emerald-200">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-emerald-700 mb-1">MAG</h4>
              <p class="text-slate-600 text-xs">
                <strong>Myelin-associated glycoprotein.</strong> Binds GT1b/GD1a on axon surfaces. 
                <strong>Key proof that GT1b is exposed extracellularly</strong> ‚Äî not locked 
                inside cells!
              </p>
              <p class="text-emerald-600 text-[10px] mt-1">
                <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18623174/" target="_blank" class="hover:underline">Schnaar & Lopez 2009</a>
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-emerald-100 rounded p-4 text-sm">
            <h4 class="font-bold text-emerald-800 mb-2">üîë Signaling Endosomes ‚Äî The Key Concept</h4>
            <p class="text-emerald-700">
              When neurons receive neurotrophins (NGF, BDNF), the receptor complex is internalized into 
              <strong>"signaling endosomes"</strong> that travel retrogradely to the nucleus with the 
              message "Survive!". <strong>GT1b is a critical membrane component</strong> of these endosomes, 
              protecting the receptor from degradation during transport.
            </p>
            <p class="text-emerald-800 font-semibold mt-2">
              Implication: Anything that binds GT1b gains access to this vital "survival signal highway."
            </p>
          </div>

          <!-- Illustration: Retrograde Feedback Signal -->
          <figure class="mt-6">
            <img 
              src="/images/Retrogra-feedback-signal.png" 
              alt="Retrograde feedback signal via GT1b at sensory nerve ending (Golgi tendon organ)"
              class="w-full rounded-lg border border-emerald-200 shadow-lg"
            />
            <figcaption class="text-sm text-emerald-700 mt-3 text-center">
              <strong>The Neurotrophin Highway:</strong> At a sensory nerve ending (here: Golgi tendon organ), 
              GT1b mediates the "handshake" with target tissue. Signaling endosomes capture trophic signals 
              and transport them retrogradely to the cell body. This same pathway can be hijacked by 
              pathogens or vaccine antigens with GT1b affinity.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>

        <!-- NEW SECTION: Electrostatic Transport Mechanism -->
        <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-blue-800 mb-4">‚ö° The Electrostatic Transport Mechanism ‚Äî Why Vesicles Beat Free Proteins</h3>
          
          <p class="text-blue-700 text-sm mb-4">
            <strong>Established science:</strong> B-series gangliosides don't just passively sit in membranes ‚Äî 
            they transform vesicles into sophisticated, electrostatically stabilized transport units.
          </p>

          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-4">
            <div class="bg-white rounded p-4 border border-blue-200">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-blue-800 mb-2">üîã Zeta-Potential: The Electrostatic Motor</h4>
              <p class="text-slate-700 text-sm mb-2">
                B-series gangliosides are <strong>polysialylated</strong>: GT1b has 3 sialic acids, GQ1b has 4. 
                Each sialic acid carries a <strong>negative charge</strong> at physiological pH.
              </p>
              <p class="text-slate-700 text-sm mb-2">
                Result: Vesicles coated with GT1b have an extremely high <strong>negative surface charge</strong> 
                (measured as "Zeta-potential").
              </p>
              <p class="text-blue-700 text-xs font-medium">
                According to DLVO theory, this prevents aggregation and enables smooth diffusion through 
                the negatively charged extracellular matrix.
              </p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="bg-white rounded p-4 border border-blue-200">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-blue-800 mb-2">üõ°Ô∏è The "Faraday Cage" Effect</h4>
              <p class="text-slate-700 text-sm mb-2">
                Free neurotrophins (often positively charged) would be quickly <strong>captured by the 
                negatively charged ECM</strong> (heparan sulfate proteoglycans) and lose range.
              </p>
              <p class="text-slate-700 text-sm mb-2">
                Inside a GT1b-rich vesicle, neurotrophins are <strong>shielded</strong> from:
              </p>
              <ul class="text-slate-600 text-xs space-y-1 ml-4 list-disc">
                <li>Extracellular proteases</li>
                <li>Non-specific ECM binding</li>
                <li>Premature receptor activation</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-blue-100 rounded p-4 mb-4">
            <h4 class="font-bold text-blue-800 mb-2">üì¶ Selective Sorting: EVs Are Not Random</h4>
            <p class="text-blue-700 text-sm mb-2">
              Exosomes form from <strong>lipid raft</strong> regions of endosomal membranes. Gangliosides, 
              with their ceramide anchors, partition strongly into these rafts. Studies show neuronal 
              exosomes are <strong>enriched in GT1b and GM1</strong> compared to the parent cell membrane.
            </p>
            <p class="text-blue-600 text-xs">
              <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22267733/" target="_blank" class="hover:underline">
                Yuyama et al. 2012 ‚Äî J Biol Chem
              </a>
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-gradient-to-r from-emerald-100 to-blue-100 rounded p-4 border border-emerald-300">
            <h4 class="font-bold text-emerald-800 mb-2">üéÅ The "Complete Signal Kit" ‚Äî Ligand + Cofactor Delivery</h4>
            <p class="text-slate-700 text-sm mb-2">
              The most elegant aspect: When a GT1b-rich vesicle carrying BDNF arrives at a target cell, 
              it doesn't just deliver the neurotrophin. It simultaneously provides the <strong>lipid 
              cofactor (GT1b)</strong> required for optimal TrkB receptor activation.
            </p>
            <p class="text-slate-700 text-sm mb-2">
              <strong>Known:</strong> TrkB receptors must translocate to lipid rafts for efficient signaling. 
              GT1b stabilizes Trk receptor dimerization in these rafts.
            </p>
            <p class="text-emerald-700 text-sm font-medium">
              The vesicle delivers a <strong>pre-assembled signaling platform</strong> ‚Äî far more efficient 
              than a free protein diffusing randomly and hoping to find an active receptor.
            </p>
            <p class="text-slate-500 text-xs mt-2">
              <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15536059/" target="_blank" class="hover:underline">
                Poon et al. 2004 ‚Äî Neurochem Res
              </a> ¬∑ 
              <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37541456/" target="_blank" class="hover:underline">
                Iguchi et al. 2023 ‚Äî Neurochem Int
              </a>
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="mt-4 p-3 bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-400 text-sm">
            <strong class="text-amber-800">üîó Connection to the Hypothesis:</strong>
            <span class="text-amber-700">
              If vaccine antigens bind GT1b, they don't just "hitch a ride" ‚Äî they become part of 
              this sophisticated delivery system. They gain access to the same electrostatically 
              optimized transport network that neurons use for survival signals. This explains how 
              antigens can travel long distances and be <em>released</em> (not stored) at target sites.
            </span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-300 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-slate-800 mb-2">üß† Speculative Extension: The "Handshake" Hypothesis</h3>
          <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm italic mb-3">
            The following is a <strong>speculative hypothesis</strong>, not established science.
          </p>
          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-3">
            <strong>Question:</strong> Do neurons <strong>share neurotrophins trans-synaptically</strong> 
            via GT1b-containing vesicles ‚Äî a kind of "molecular handshake"?
          </p>
          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-3">
            <strong>If true:</strong> The B-series network becomes more than just a cellular mechanism ‚Äî 
            it becomes an <strong>inter-neuronal communication system</strong>. Cells would exchange 
            gangliosides and their bound cargo with neighboring cells.
          </p>
          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-0">
            <strong>Implication for the hypothesis:</strong> This would explain why GT1b-bound substances 
            (like tetanus toxin) can spread beyond the directly innervated neuron. Vaccine antigens could 
            potentially reach <em>any cell connected to this signaling network</em> ‚Äî including orexin neurons 
